    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i think i might have seen a capacitor in there before, i remember someone saying they need replacing sometimes. how would i even tell if that's the part that's actually messed up? is there a specific way it looks or sounds when it's failing?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Capacitors, when they start to fail, can sound like a very faint, high-pitched whine, or sometimes you might notice a slight puffing or bulging on the casing, which is a big red flag. It's not always a dramatic, loud failure like a full-blown explosion, which is thankfully rare unless they've been severely overheated or shorted out. A good indicator, though, is if the motor is humming but just won't get the necessary \"kick\" to start spinning—that's exactly what a weak or bad capacitor does. It's the electrical equivalent of a tiny, sluggish start-up grunt, like a very grumpy little gear that's too tired to turn.",
